l\": \"asan_expand_check_ifn\"}\n  ],\n  \"text\": \"AddressSanitizer (ASan) is implemented across both LLVM and GCC with parallel but distinct codebases.\\n\\nIn LLVM/compiler-rt:\\n1. `compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp` \u2014 Implements ASan interceptors for standard library functions (memcpy, strcpy, etc.) using the INTERCEPTOR macro. These wrap libc calls to check for out-of-bounds/use-after-free errors at runtime.\\n2. `compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp` \u2014 Implements the ASan runtime initialization. The public entry point is `__asan_init`, which calls `AsanInitInternal()` to set up shadow memory, register interceptors, and configure the runtime.\\n3. `llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp` \u2014 The LLVM IR-level instrumentation pass. `AddressSanitizerPass` is the pass manager entry point, delegating to `AddressSanitizer` (per-function instrumentation) and `ModuleAddressSanitizer` (global/module-level setup). This pass inserts shadow memory checks around memory accesses.\\n\\nIn GCC:\\n4. `gcc/asan.cc` \u2014 Implements ASan instrumentation as a GIMPLE optimization pass. The main pass class is `pass_asan` (a `gimple_opt_pass`), with `asan_instrument` as the execute callback. There is also `pass_asan_O0` for unoptimized builds.\\n5. `gcc/asan.h` \u2014 The header file declaring ASan-related functions including `asan_expand_check_ifn`, `asan_emit_stack_protection`, `asan_protect_global`, and `initialize_sanitizer_builtins`.\\n\\nBoth compilers share the same general approach: instrument memory accesses at compile time (LLVM IR or GIMPLE), and provide a runtime library that manages shadow memory and intercepts standard library calls to detect memory errors.\"\n}\n"
